Overview

The Wessex Area has been subdivided into 12 ‘Operational Catchments’. Here we focus on the Avon Bristol Urban, the figures below provide information on its geography and waterbodies, both “unmodified” and Artificial or Heavily Modified Water Bodies (A/HMWB).

1 Catchments

The Avon Bristol Urban Operational Catchment sits within the Avon Bristol and Somerset North Streams Management Catchment, which sits within the larger Severn River Basin District. It contains 14 individual EA surface waterbodies and 5 groundwater bodies.

  • Surface Water Catchments
  • Groundwater Catchments

Groundwater catchments can overlap multiple surface water catchments.

2 Geology & Topography of Catchment

The geology of a catchment determines the presence of groundwater aquifers, a catchment’s topography, and characteristics of the streams it contains (lowland clay river, chalk streams etc). The characteristics given to a river by its geology (such as natural alkalinity, substrate type etc) impact on biotic and phys-chem indicies used within WFD classifications.
